<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;"><b>16.3</b></td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;"><b> Management of financial risks</b></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">The financial risk arising from the 
Company&#8217;s
      operations are credit risk, liquidity risk, interest rate risk, currency 
risk
      and commodity price risk.&nbsp; These risks arise from the normal course 
of
      operations and all transactions undertaken are to support the 
Company&#8217;s ability
      to continue as a going concern.&nbsp; The risks associated with these 
financial
      instruments and the policies on how to mitigate these risks are set out 
below.&nbsp;
      Management manages and monitors these exposures to ensure appropriate 
measures
      are implemented on a timely and effective manner.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;"><b>Credit risk </b></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">Credit risk is the risk of an unexpected 
loss
      if a customer or counterparty to a financial instrument fails to meet its
      contractual obligations and arises primarily from the Company&#8217;s cash
and cash
      equivalents and amounts receivable.&nbsp; The Company manages its credit 
risk
      relating to cash and cash equivalents by dealing with only with highly-
rated
      financial institutions.&nbsp; As at 30 April 2013, amounts receivable was 
mainly
      comprised of Goods and Services Tax/Harmonized Sales Tax receivable and 
amounts
      receivable from related entities for shared office and administrative 
costs
      (Notes 6 and 17).&nbsp; As a result, credit risk is considered 
insignificant.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;"><b>Liquidity risk</b></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">Liquidity risk is the risk that the Company
      will not be able to meet its financial obligations as they fall due. The
      Company manages liquidity risk by continuously monitoring actual and 
projected
      cash flows and matching the maturity profile of financial assets and
      liabilities.&nbsp; As at 30 April 2013, the Company had $848,953 (30 April
2012:
      $3,440,410) in cash and cash equivalents to settle current liabilities of
      $75,355 (30 April 2012: $413,715) and, accordingly, liquidity risk is
      considered insignificant.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;"><b>Currency risk</b></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">The Company is exposed to currency risk to 
the extent of its
      acquisition and exploration expenditures on its US properties and African
      property.&nbsp; The Company&#8217;s expenditures will be negatively 
impacted if the US
      dollar increases versus the Canadian dollar.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">The majority of the
      Company&#8217;s cash flows and financial assets and liabilities are 
denominated in
      Canadian dollars, which is the Company&#8217;s functional and reporting 
currency.&nbsp;
      Foreign currency risk is limited to the portion of the Company&#8217;s 
business
      transactions denominated in currencies other than the Canadian dollar. 
</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p align="right" id="pg2">Page | 42</p>
<hr noshade size="4" color="#000" style="page-break-after:always">
<a name="page_Page%20%7C%2043">&nbsp;</a>
<table style="font-size: 10pt;" width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" 
cellspacing="0">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td style="border-bottom:solid black 1px;"><b><font size="4">Pacific North 
West Capital Corp.</font> <br>
      Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements <br>
      </b> 30 April 2013<br>
      (Expressed in Canadian dollars) </td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">The Company&#8217;s objective in managing 
its foreign currency risk is to
      minimize its net exposures to foreign currency cash flows by holding most 
of
      its cash and cash equivalents in Canadian dollars (Note 5).&nbsp; The 
Company
      monitors and forecasts the values of net foreign currency cash flow and 
balance
      sheet exposures and from time to time could authorize the use of 
derivative
      financial instruments such as forward foreign exchange contracts to
      economically hedge a portion of foreign currency fluctuations.&nbsp; The 
Company has
      not, to the date of these consolidated financial statements, entered into
      derivative instruments to offset the impact of foreign currency 
fluctuations.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;"><b>Other risks</b></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">Unless otherwise noted, it is 
management&#8217;s
      opinion that the Company is not exposed to significant interest rate risk 
and
      commodity price risk arising from financial instruments.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"

<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:1.0in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">Each flow-through unit (the &#8220;FT 
Unit&#8221;) at a price of $0.05 per FT
      Unit will consist of one common flow-through share and one-half of one
      non-flow-through, non-transferable, share purchase warrant (the 
&#8220;Warrant&#8221;),
      with each Warrant entitling the holder to purchase one additional
      non-flow-through common share of the Company at a price of $0.10 per share
for
      a period of 12 months from the closing date.&nbsp; The proceeds from the 
sale of the
      FT Units will be used for the further development and exploration of the 
River
      Valley PGM Project and the exploration of the two large adjacent
properties.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

      Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements <br>
      </b> 30 April 2013<br>
      (Expressed in Canadian dollars) </td>
  </tr>

border="0" id="table">
  <tr valign="top">
    <td nowrap style="width:1.0in;">&nbsp;</td>
    <td style="text-align:justify;">Each non-flow-through unit (the &#8220;NFT 
Unit&#8221;) at a price of $0.05 per
      NFT Unit will consist of one common share and one-half of one non-
transferable Warrant,
      with each Warrant entitling the holder to purchase one common share of the
      Company at a price of $0.10 per share for a period of 12 months from the
      closing date.&nbsp; The proceeds from the sale of the NFT Units will be 
used as
      working capital and for funding other properties.</td>
  </tr>

<head>

TO<br></b><b>SECTION 302 OF THE SARBANES-OXLEY

<p align="justify">I,
Harry Barr, certify that:</p>

report on Form 20-F, for the period ended April 30, 2013, of Pacific North West
Capital Corp. (the &#8220;Company&#8221;)</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">2.</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">Based
on my knowledge, this report does not contain any untrue statement of a
material fact or omit to state a material fact necessary to make the statements
made, in light of the circumstances under which such statements were made, not
misleading with respect to the period covered by this report;</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">3.</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">Based
on my knowledge, the financial statements, and other financial information
included in this report, fairly present in all material respects the financial
condition, results of operations and cash flows of the Company as of, and for,
the periods presented in this report.</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">4.</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">The
Company&#8217;s other certifying officer(s) and I are responsible for 
establishing
and maintaining disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Exchange Act
Rules 13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e)) and internal control over financial reporting
(as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f)) for the Company and
have:</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
<td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">a)</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">Designed
such disclosure controls and procedures, or caused such disclosure controls and
procedures to be designed under our supervision, to ensure that material
information relating to the Company, including its consolidated subsidiaries,
is made known to us by others within those entities, particularly during the
period in which this report is being prepared;</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
<td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">b)</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">Designed
such internal control over financial reporting, or caused such internal control
over financial reporting to be designed under our supervision, to provide
reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the
preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with
generally accepted accounting principles;</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
<td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">c)</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">Evaluated
the effectiveness of the Company&#8217;s disclosure controls and procedures and
presented in this report our conclusions about the effectiveness of the
disclosure controls and procedures, as of the end of the period covered by this
report based on such evaluation; and</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
<td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">d)</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">Disclosed
in this annual report any change in the Company&#8217;s internal control over
financial reporting that occurred during the period covered by the report that
has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, the
Company&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting; and.</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br>
<table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0" 
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">5.</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">The
Company&#8217;s other certifying officer(s) and I have disclosed, based on our 
most
recent evaluation of internal control over financial reporting, to the 
Company&#8217;s
auditors and the audit committee of the Company&#8217;s board of directors (or
persons performing the equivalent functions):</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
<td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">a)</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">All
significant deficiencies and material weaknesses in the design or operation of
internal control over financial reporting which are reasonably likely to
adversely affect the Company&#8217;s ability to record, process, summarize and 
report
financial information; and</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<br><table cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="font-size: 10pt;" cellspacing="0"
border="0" id="">
              <tr valign="top">
              <td style="width:0.5in;">&nbsp;</td>
<td nowrap style="width:0.5in;">b)</td>
<td style="text-align:justify;">Any
fraud, whether or not material, that involves management or other employees who
have a significant role in the Company&#8217;s internal control over financial
reporting.</td>
              </tr>
</table>
<p align="justify">Date:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; July 29, 2013</p>
<p align="justify"><b>PACIFIC NORTH WEST CAPITAL CORP.</b></p>

<TYPE>EX-12.5
<SEQUENCE>6
<FILENAME>exhibit12-5.htm
<DESCRIPTION>CERTIFICATE OF ETHICS
<TEXT>
<html>
<head>
<title>Filed by Avantafile.com - Pacific North West Capital Corp. - Exhibit 
12.5</title>
</head>
<body style="font-size: 10pt; ">
<hr style="border: 2px solid black; font-size: 2pt;">
<hr style="border: 1px solid black; font-size: 1pt;">
<p align="right"><b>Exhibit 12.5</b></p>
<p align="center"><b>CERTIFICATE OF ETHICS FOR THE CHIEF EXECUTIVE
  OFFICER<br></b><b>AND THE CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER</b></p>
<p align="justify">In
  my role as Chief Executive Officer (&#8220;CEO&#8221;) or Chief Financial 
Officer (&#8220;CFO&#8221;) of
  Pacific North West Capital Corp. (the &#8220;Company&#8221;), I have adhered 
to and
  advocated to the best of my knowledge and ability the following principles and
  responsibilities governing professional conduct and ethics:</p>
<p align="justify">Act with honesty and
  integrity, handling in an ethical manner any actual or apparent conflicts of
  interest between personal and professional relationships.&nbsp; A 
&#8220;conflict of
  interest&#8221; exists when an individual&#8217;s private interests interfere 
or conflict
  in any way (or even appear to interfere or conflict) with the interests of the
  Company.</p>
<p align="justify">Provide constituents
  with information that is accurate, complete, objective, relevant, timely and
  understandable.&nbsp; If I am the CEO or CFO, I shall review the 
Company&#8217;s annual
  reports before certifying and filing them with the SEC.</p>
<p align="justify">Comply with all
  applicable laws, rules and regulations of federal, provincial, territorial,
  state and local governments, and other appropriate private and public
  regulatory agencies.</p>
<p align="justify">Act in good faith,
  responsibly, with due care, competence and diligence, without misrepresenting
  material facts or allowing my independent judgment to be subordinated.</p>
<p align="justify">Respect the
  confidentiality of information acquired in the course of business except when
  authorized or otherwise legally obligated to disclose the information.&nbsp; I
  acknowledge that confidential information acquired in the course of business 
is
  not to be used for personal advantage.</p>
<p align="justify">Promote ethical
  behavior among employees at the Company and as a responsible partner with
  industry peers and associates.</p>
<p align="justify">Maintain control over
  and responsibly manage all assets and resources employed or entrusted to me by
  the Company.</p>
<p align="justify">Report illegal or
  unethical conduct by any director, officer or employee that has occurred, is
  occurring or may occur, including any potential violations of the 
Company&#8217;s
  Code of Business Conduct and Ethics (the &#8220;Code&#8221;).&nbsp; Such 
report shall be made to
  the Audit Committee of the Board of Directors and shall include conduct of a
  financial or non-financial nature.</p>
<p align="justify">Comply with the Code.&nbsp;
  I understand that if I violate any part of the Code, I will be subject to
  disciplinary action.</p>
<p align="justify">I understand that the
  Code is subject to all applicable laws, rules and regulations.</p>
<p align="justify">I understand that
  there shall be no waiver of, modification of, or change to any part of the 
Code
  except by a vote of the Board of Directors or a designated Board 
committee.&nbsp; In
  the event that a waiver of, modification of, or a change to the Code is
  granted, then the notice of the waiver, modification and/or change shall be
  posted on the Company&#8217;s website within five business days of the Board 
of
  Directors&#8217; or designated Board committee&#8217;s vote or shall be 
disclosed otherwise
  as required by applicable law or Stock Exchange or SEC rules.&nbsp; Notices 
posted
  on the Company website shall remain there for a period of 12 months and shall
  be retained in the Company&#8217;s files as required by law.</p>
<table style="font-size: 10pt;" width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" 
cellspacing="0"
>
  <tr valign="top">
    <td style="width:50%;"><p><i>/s/
      Harry Barr</i><br>
      __________________________
      <br>
      Harry
  Barr<br>
    Chief
  Executive Officer<br>
    <br>
    July 29,
  2013&nbsp;</p></td>
    <td>/s/ <i>Robert
    Guanzon<br>
    __________________________<br>
    Robert
  Guanzon<br>
    Chief
  Financial Officer<br>
    <br>
    July
  29, 2013</i></td>
  </tr>

<p align="justify"><b>Consent
of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</b></p>
<p align="justify">We consent to the incorporation of our report dated 22 July 
2013 with
respect to the consolidated financial statements of Pacific North West Capital
Corp. (the &#8220;Company&#8221;), which comprise the consolidated statements of
financial
position as at 30 April 2013 and 2012 and the consolidated statements of loss
and comprehensive loss, cash flows and changes in equity for the years ended 30
April 2013 and 2012, in the Annual Report on Form 20-F of the Company dated 23
July 2013.&nbsp; </p>
